   - routes
      - user_routes.py
   - extension
      - db.py 
   - schemas
      - user_schema


- pip install marshmallow

- pip install Flask-JWT-Extended

- generating secret_key :
- type python on bash
0 >>> import secrets
>>> secret_key = secrets.token_hex(32)
>>> print(secret_key)
08d6a07b5e11d987a49b05f3b25f0d71da9e0747038a0e8cec8a474ab066297a

- create a new file auth_resource.py --> jwt logic

- POST http://127.0.0.1:5000/auth/register --> registered below user

 - {
    "name": "Sanchita",
    "email": "s@gmail.com",
    "mobile": 873443,
    "salary": 844244,
    "password": "Sanchita"
}

- GET http://127.0.0.1:5000/auth/login --> login using your email and passowrd as you created in code

 - {
    "email": "s@gmail.com",
    "password": "Sanchita"
}
 

- http://127.0.0.1:5000/auth/protected

{
  "access_token": "<JWT_TOKEN_HERE>"
}

- use your token 
 - GET http://127.0.0.1:5000/auth/protected
   Headers:
   Authorization: Bearer eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...

- you get the message as see below:
{
    "message": "Hello user 9, you are logged in!"
}

- now you will be able to access all your protected routes through postman

- when you try accessing swagger, you need to provide autherization - add Bearer <jwt_token>

soft delete url --> http://127.0.0.1:5000/users/soft/3 
 - defined a separate end point to diffrentiate b/w delete and soft delete, else soft would work like delete only
